When importing sub-tasks in a CSV file, if the parent issue already exists in JIRA and has a Fix Version set, and in the import process the FixVersion field is not mapped, the field is overwritten. 
In our documentation regarding [CSV import|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Importing+Data+from+CSV] we state: 
{quote}Importing a CSV to update existing issues will reset columns to their default values if they are not specified in the CSV.{quote}

However, this seems to be true only to the Fix Version field. If we import issues in the same condition and the Assignee field is not mapped, it is not overwritten.

As per the subject. On the database you should have two or more duplicated FogBugz projects.

Steps to reproduce:
- Start a FogBugz import setting properly the database information from SQL Server (haven't tested against MySQL or another databases). Click in next;

Current behavior:
- The page is poorly rendered;
- No JIRA project will be listed for match with a FogBugz project;
- Nothing happens when clicking on the "select all" checkbox (to select/un-select all the FogBugz projects);UnresolvedUnresolved

Expected behavior:
- The page *must* display an warning advising that the database has two duplicated FogBugz projects;
- From a customer perspective, if it's possible to proceed even with duplicated FogBugz projects, the user must be able to match the FogBugz project with a JIRA project (and import the data).
- The page needs to be properly rendered;
- The checkbox for select/un-select the FogBugz project *must* works for any case.

We have a related [JIRA KB|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRAKB/FogBugz+Import+fails+with+SQL+Syntax+error] with a related stack trace for importing FogBugz data from MySQL. I'm still getting the updated logs from the SQL Server occurrence (if we have any).

Best regards,
Lucas Timm
Atlassian Support

